"Security software has been the defence of choice for enterprises for many years in order to protect data and safeguard both devices and networks from malware. This is understandable – for some time, layering software has been the safest and easiest security solution. The cyber-security landscape, however, does not sleep, and is constantly evolving – there have been various developments, including Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) and increasingly penetrable network perimeters. Add to these, economic and legal developments – a more mobile workforce, and EU data protection laws on the horizon – and software-based architectures appear more and more unable to properly face the current state of cyberthreats. However, enterprises can now use the hardware within their devices for security purposes, and new operating systems, such as Windows 8, have made this approach a more practical option. Security software has been the defence of choice for enterprises for many years – for some time layering software has been the safest and easiest security solution. However, the threats organisations face are evolving. Enterprises can now use the hardware within their devices for security purposes. Joseph Souren of Wave Systems explains how you can use hardware features such as Self Encrypting Drives (SEDs) and Trusted Platform Modules (TPMs) to make your organisation more secure."
